[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Improving coverage rules**\n\nI see that I need to enhance coverage and approach this by ensuring that I’m not using reflection directly unless the public API requires it. I’m considering whether using MethodHandle might be disallowed. Currently, it seems like the dynamic report isn’t functioning as expected either. I’ve got to tackle this carefully to avoid any missteps while improving my coverage approach. Let’s make sure I’m sticking to the rules!\n\n**Analyzing static initialization**\n\nThe active call site is a static initializer for LOG assigned using LogFactory.getLog(ExpectContinueMethod.class). To achieve coverage, the class must be initialized at runtime with a null field. I realized that referencing ExpectContinueMethod.class doesn’t trigger its initialization because class literals don't initialize. Instantiating a subclass should trigger the superclass initialization. However, if this happens at build time, Class.forName won't run at runtime. I wonder if our broad build.gradle configuration is problematic. Additionally, for native image runtime, all supertypes and subtypes need consideration.\n\n**Exploring class initialization issues**\n\nAt build time, it seems the class could be initialized via reflection with MethodHandle. I’m considering whether the test, using MethodHandles.privateLookupIn during the native image build, initializes the test code. It looks like the dynamic-access tool possibly doesn’t recognize synthetic calls as from the frame, which is unclear. Since the user indicated no coverage after their second attempt, the class likely initialized at build time despite using buildArgs. Moving forward, I think using a fresh class loader, like URLClassLoader for dynamic loading, might help. However, I need to keep in mind that dynamic class loading isn't supported in Native Image.\n\n**Assessing dynamic access coverage**\n\nIn the JVM, I should expect the class to load, but in the native image, unsupported features might lead to no coverage. It seems that dynamic access coverage is likely limited to the JVM or native contexts. For this to work correctly, it probably needs to execute calls under the JVM agent. I wonder if the dynamic access report comes from the native compile instrumentation running on the JVM. Also, does using a fresh class loader in the JVM actually count?", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_039cb3760e0edf13016a0495fd1be481a199be07f3522f382a\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqBJYIpNHUeNXkzvpq0dxhHhWKiURITWOW9C5GnMaWCqIGgV0HCfcqNagwL4QefviU2kXS75U2fYhRrOpMT05WNMNGecceKH8y0W3IIjKUX6mdMntwxFdapfb5lhVtGci2E-R3nR4xBwP9yxReSqwLRFmUTmx7mXCwLE0xjsrSuQ2C6Mb7hPNftTV5mJLMQe-6shiQyikDZ8UhSSbRMTK6VZcZu0LHB5WzZ5YdpDdZassw04FW1jNn0jM5XGhwR-2gYaiKwyyRZ0fnPaxG3PN0FOFzSWTVOiqVRw0Z9yj9IrTep-Q1UVssm3HcI4SrWyZHsclfOtfbHMjxqSrEpP3Nb4WXXGAxBMQlmixiEb72L5L8BpERl_Z-t2LqWBT-9MHOYHhnj7avMZeZox64aAW0K3IF9oRCt2vgjw8pLnj5YPKeZfrvVPfH0Q-tPiSzN-eam4wNqgd6PdpGioCDcNoeHE8YnM6Lt3CWk7ED02mYfK1c6jRARFQ46u8cLnmaGVEoABRm0Xl987Du34XEP6d9zS1NT7doyLrBrv008aYkenRTXQYKVDb0UmzujnP1QMu-SLaxm2MVNP2Gao6DCWjWBCNYg56BVRG2XCI1dIhUK37rs5kZPg4fWsmwKCEGgR7YXUp11MTG6Kuri3v0-RDGjER8tWuBQ5pytO3Az2V4rukSv6b7NgD3ZuvfkfjHk-7CZZaP0Q4mG5-xCgkznFMqeDEefl6lfEruOCD3HwD5N4nro2flkGlXrZYlim6nq4wvfdF9yhEydHgnKgLDF1EgMl899G0fVpFFJ4qOyMMantdxNdW6bKtsvDLnCX1o1yR18oG--zf4XCdSSi7YItYcIwqNI2B0psCFK7OHv2S8fgKLJvC7S_JVqeFxzMEZvshaivZhhUt5neY6Lrx2p5SMnUbnbFUU3b2EXHAV1ZnL1pQvGdzVd9JC7p4jxWgiFsa4jmgdh1YRr7GC0NrnZd2yuhCP-zKAoXs_lrZvCu-Wv52K0hSLjd6LJF-7R0_twft5-qYBJILZeWwq0394OxpMnXKZTxIYWwituDFCEY9uNjuwmt7ts1H6Stlwsomkn3UJl1vFXpY-b137o5GfJ-cfD7bD2mGeoL7noYQVziFIq0CJQiOEnlyrK1YpDZkCKdRXVhhNxGJZY38x9HSVAWfUAqM0_cc5ztMxPulk24ZaxxvN3s9QIKwXPOLjlDAHyqL65FzFhFjFXEkyQCBUNyrt2teRf77aLoEDzOzHJC08VAD2OSdrJtglp4R3D2qtTYA9fGAVuaYrRZlKOdOq3aJtYjxQbb03ryZR9PUQBfzjZDqnyWW6quHyCXyCFhWgDRRcqSUBaQ7Zaa4D6mmG54YxJC9aVrr2PKwnEB4j8e8a_ddyamTOA85aLvdypywKw